=========================================================
C++ TYPE CASTING (TYPE CONVERSION) – COMPLETE INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================================

C++ provides 4 main casting operators:

1. static_cast
2. dynamic_cast
3. const_cast
4. reinterpret_cast

PLUS:
- C-style cast (legacy, unsafe)

=========================================================
1. static_cast ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ (MOST USED)
=========================================================

Use cases:
- Compile-time conversion
- Numeric conversions
- Upcasting in inheritance ( derived to base) ***

Syntax:
static_cast<type>(expression)

---------------------------------------------------------
Example 1: primitive conversion
---------------------------------------------------------
int a = 10;
double b = static_cast<double>(a);

---------------------------------------------------------
Example 2: upcasting (safe)
---------------------------------------------------------
class Base {};
class Derived : public Base {};

Base* b = static_cast<Base*>(new Derived);

Base* b = static_cast<Base*>(new Derived);

👉 is technically unnecessary and not recommended

Because upcasting is ALWAYS implicit in C++

---------------------------------------------------------
Important points:
- Checked at compile time only
- No runtime type safety
- Fast
- Safe only when you are sure about types

=========================================================
2. dynamic_cast ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ (RUNTIME SAFE CASTING)
=========================================================

Use cases:
- Runtime polymorphism (RTTI)
- Downcasting safely

Requirements:
- Must have at least one virtual function

Syntax:
dynamic_cast<type>(expression)

---------------------------------------------------------
Example:
---------------------------------------------------------
class Base {
public:
    virtual void show() {}
};

class Derived : public Base {};

Base* b = new Derived;

Derived* d = dynamic_cast<Derived*>(b);

---------------------------------------------------------
If invalid:
- returns nullptr (for pointers)
- throws bad_cast (for references)

---------------------------------------------------------
Important points:
- Slower (runtime check)
- Safe
- Used in polymorphic classes

=========================================================
3. const_cast ⭐⭐⭐⭐ (REMOVE CONST)
=========================================================

Use case:
- Remove const or volatile qualifier

Syntax:
const_cast<type>(expression)

---------------------------------------------------------
Example:
---------------------------------------------------------
void func(int* p)
{
    *p = 20;
}

const int a = 10;

func(const_cast<int*>(&a));

---------------------------------------------------------
Important points:
- ONLY modifies const/volatile qualifiers
- Does NOT change actual object constness safely
- Misuse leads to undefined behavior

=========================================================
4. reinterpret_cast ⭐⭐⭐ (MOST DANGEROUS)
=========================================================

Use case:
- Low-level casting
- Pointer to pointer conversion
- Address manipulation

Syntax:
reinterpret_cast<type>(expression)

---------------------------------------------------------
Example:
---------------------------------------------------------
int a = 10;

char* p = reinterpret_cast<char*>(&a);

---------------------------------------------------------
Important points:
- No safety checks
- Just reinterprets memory bits
- Highly unsafe
- Used in:
  - hardware programming
  - serialization
  - network packets

=========================================================
5. C-STYLE CAST (OLD STYLE)
=========================================================

Syntax:
(type) expression

Example:
int x = (int)3.14;

---------------------------------------------------------
Problem:
- Can behave like any of the above casts
- No clarity
- Unsafe

=========================================================
COMPARISON TABLE (VERY IMPORTANT)
=========================================================

Cast               Safety     Speed     Use case
---------------------------------------------------------
static_cast        Medium     Fast      general conversions
dynamic_cast       High       Slow      polymorphism
const_cast         Low        Fast      remove const
reinterpret_cast   Very Low   Fast      low-level memory

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q. Why do we need type casting?
A.
To convert one data type into another safely or explicitly.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Difference between static_cast and dynamic_cast?

static_cast:
- compile-time
- unsafe for downcasting

dynamic_cast:
- runtime
- safe for polymorphism

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why is dynamic_cast slow?
A.
Because it performs runtime type checking using RTTI.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why is reinterpret_cast dangerous?
A.
Because it only reinterprets memory without type safety.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. When do we use const_cast?
A.
To remove const/volatile qualifier.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Which cast should be preferred in C++?
A.
Always prefer:
- static_cast for normal conversions
- dynamic_cast for polymorphism

Avoid C-style casts.

=========================================================
REAL-WORLD USE CASES
=========================================================

static_cast:
- numeric conversions
- type-safe conversions
- upcasting

dynamic_cast:
- plugin systems
- GUI frameworks
- runtime polymorphism checks

const_cast:
- legacy APIs
- C library compatibility

reinterpret_cast:
- device drivers
- networking
- serialization

